<p>Sal Soghoian, writing for MacStories:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Here‚Äôs a thought experiment. Let‚Äôs imagine that Apple decided to combine their engineering resources to form app teams that delivered both iOS and macOS versions of applications.</p>

  <p>In such a scenario it may seem logical to retain application features common to both platforms and to remove those that were perceived to require extra resources. Certainly Automation would be something examined in that regard, and the idea might be posited that: ‚ÄúApp Extensions are equivalent to, or could be a replacement for, User Automation in macOS.‚Äù And by User Automation, I‚Äôm referring to Apple Event scripting, Automator, Services, the UNIX command line utilities, etc.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I‚Äôve said many times that one of the main reasons I came to OS X is the underlying Unix utilities. I literally <em>can‚Äôt do my job</em> without the command line. It‚Äôs always in my dock, it‚Äôs always open, and I‚Äôve got it customized just the way I like it. There is no replacement for the terminal, and no App Extension can provide a way for me to string together the tools I use to get done what needs to get done.</p>

<p>In such a world like Sal is imagining, I would have to find an SSH app like Prompt and setup my entire development environment on a Linux server somewhere. While possible, it‚Äôs not economical and it‚Äôs certainly not how I‚Äôve become accustomed to working. I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôm alone in this either, anyone who does web development relies on command line versions of Python, Ruby, PHP, or Perl, along with a host of other small utilities to do things like syntax checking or unit tests.</p>

<p>I think it‚Äôs possible that Apple could remove the Terminal from OS X, along with the Unix utilities, similar to what they‚Äôve done with iOS, but I don‚Äôt think they will. Apple uses OS X to develop their own software, so they know what the developers need to be efficient and productive. However I could see a world where you had to install Xcode and enable ‚Äúdeveloper mode‚Äù to get to the Unix utilities. We may not be far away from a day when OS X no longer ships with Terminal.app, but I think we‚Äôll always have a way to install it when there‚Äôs real work that needs done.</p>

<p>I think Apple may be heading in the wrong direction, and it‚Äôs sad to see Sal be let go, but I‚Äôm glad to see him carrying on fighting for the users.</p>

